{"cells":[{"source":"---\n# 1. What is Data Engineering — and Why Does It Exist?\n\n## Let's start with a story 📖\n\nImagine you're working at a company that runs an online store.\nEvery day:\n- Thousands of orders come in from the website\n- Customer support logs complaints in a separate tool\n- The warehouse tracks inventory in a spreadsheet\n- Marketing runs ads and logs clicks in yet another system\n\nThe CEO walks in one Monday and asks:\n> *\"What was our best-selling product last month, broken down by region?\"*\n\nWithout a data engineer, someone has to:\n1. Manually export CSVs from 4 different systems\n2. Spend 2 days cleaning and merging them in Excel\n3. Hope they didn't make a mistake\n4. Do it all again next Monday\n\n**That's the problem Data Engineering solves.**\n\n---\n\n## So what IS Data Engineering?\n\n**Data Engineering** is the practice of building and maintaining the systems\nthat move, store, and prepare data so it's always ready to be used.\n\nA data engineer would:\n- Set up **automated pipelines** that pull data from all 4 systems every hour\n- Store everything in a **central data warehouse**\n- Clean and transform the data automatically\n- So the CEO can get their answer in **2 seconds** instead of 2 days\n\n```\nBEFORE Data Engineering          AFTER Data Engineering\n──────────────────────           ──────────────────────\nOrders DB     ┐                  Orders DB  ─┐\nSupport tool  ├──► Manual work   Support    ─┼──► Pipeline ──► Warehouse ──► Dashboard\nSpreadsheet   │    (days)        Spreadsheet─┤    (auto)      (always        (seconds)\nAd platform   ┘                  Ad platform─┘                 fresh)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Where does DE sit in the data world?\n\nThink of it like building a city's plumbing system:\n\n```\n🏙️ City (Company)\n│\n├── 🚰 Plumbing / Infrastructure  ← DATA ENGINEER (that's you!)\n│       Water comes from many sources, gets filtered, stored in tanks,\n│       and delivered clean to every building.\n│\n├── 🏠 Buildings (Apps & Dashboards)  ← Use the clean water\n│\n└── 👨‍🔬 Scientists testing water quality  ← DATA SCIENTISTS\n        They need the water to already be clean to do their work.\n```\n\n> ✅ **The key insight:** Data scientists and analysts get all the glory,\n> but **none of their work is possible without the data engineer building the foundation first.**\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"78726954-040c-49ae-b288-a4549567a35d"},{"source":"---\n# 2. What Does a Data Engineer Actually Do All Day?\n\nLet's be honest — job descriptions are confusing. Let's break it down simply.\n\n## A typical day for a Data Engineer:\n\n### 🌅 Morning: Check if pipelines ran successfully overnight\n```\n\"Did the nightly sales sync complete?\"\n\"Are there any failed jobs in Airflow?\"\n\"Did the new data pass quality checks?\"\n```\n\n### 🛠️ Midday: Build or fix something\n```\n\"The marketing team needs data from a new API — build an ingestion pipeline\"\n\"The dashboard is slow — optimize the SQL query or restructure the table\"\n\"A schema changed upstream — update the pipeline to handle it\"\n```\n\n### 🤝 Afternoon: Collaborate\n```\n\"Help the data scientist understand where the training data comes from\"\n\"Sit with the analyst to build the new revenue report table\"\n\"Review a teammate's pull request for a new transformation\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## How a Data Engineer differs from similar roles:\n\n| Role | Analogy | Main Question They Answer |\n|------|---------|---------------------------|\n| **Data Engineer** | Builds the kitchen | *\"How do we reliably get clean ingredients here?\"* |\n| **Data Analyst** | Cooks the meal | *\"What does this data tell us?\"* |\n| **Data Scientist** | Creates new recipes | *\"Can we predict future outcomes?\"* |\n| **ML Engineer** | Opens a restaurant chain | *\"How do we serve this prediction at scale?\"* |\n\n---\n\n## Skills you'll need (don't worry — we'll cover these)\n\n```\nMUST HAVE                    GOOD TO HAVE\n──────────                   ────────────\n✅ Python                    ⭐ Scala (for Spark jobs)\n✅ SQL (intermediate+)       ⭐ Docker & Kubernetes\n✅ One cloud platform        ⭐ Data modeling theory\n   (AWS / GCP / Azure)       ⭐ Streaming (Kafka)\n✅ A pipeline tool           ⭐ Cloud certifications\n   (Airflow / Prefect)\n✅ A warehouse\n   (Snowflake / BigQuery)\n```\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"892a40bf-2485-4685-ad90-b73f35dc9c98"},{"source":"---\n# 3. Core Concepts — The Vocabulary You Must Know\n\nBefore we write any real pipelines, we need to speak the language.\nLet's go through each concept with a real-world analogy.\n\n---\n\n## 📦 3.1 — Structured vs Semi-Structured vs Unstructured Data\n\nThink of data like documents in an office:\n\n| Type | Office Analogy | Data Example | Tool Friendly? |\n|------|---------------|--------------|----------------|\n| **Structured** | A filled-in form with fixed fields | SQL table, CSV | ✅ Very easy |\n| **Semi-Structured** | A handwritten note with some patterns | JSON, XML | 🟡 Needs parsing |\n| **Unstructured** | A random pile of photos and voice memos | Images, audio, video | ❌ Very hard |\n\n---\n\n## ⏱️ 3.2 — Batch Processing vs Stream Processing\n\nThis is one of the **most important distinctions** in DE.\n\n### Batch Processing — \"Collect now, process later\"\nLike doing laundry: you let it pile up all week, then wash it all at once on Sunday.\n\n```\nEvents happen throughout the day:\n  Order 1 (9:00am)  ──┐\n  Order 2 (11:30am) ──┤\n  Order 3 (2:15pm)  ──┤── collected ──► Processed at midnight ──► Report ready\n  Order 4 (6:45pm)  ──┘\n\n✅ Simple, cheaper to run\n❌ Data is always hours/days old\nUse when: Daily reports, monthly billing, data warehouse loads\n```\n\n### Stream Processing — \"Process as it happens\"\nLike a security guard watching a live camera feed — they react immediately.\n\n```\n  Order 1 (9:00am)  ──► processed immediately ──► Alert sent\n  Order 2 (9:00:03) ──► processed immediately ──► Alert sent\n  Order 3 (9:00:07) ──► processed immediately ──► Alert sent\n\n✅ Real-time insights\n❌ More complex, more expensive\nUse when: Fraud detection, live dashboards, IoT sensors\n```\n\n---\n\n## 📋 3.3 — What is a Schema?\n\nA **schema** is the \"contract\" that defines what your data looks like.\nIt's like the column headers on a form — before you fill it in, you define what goes where.\n\n```\nWithout schema:                    With schema:\n───────────────                    ────────────\nname: \"Alice\"                      name:       VARCHAR(100)   ← must be text\nage:  \"twenty eight\"  ❌           age:        INTEGER        ← must be a number\nemail: \"not an email\" ❌           email:      VARCHAR(255)   ← must contain @\n                                   created_at: TIMESTAMP      ← must be a date\n```\n\n> 💡 Schemas enforce **data contracts** — they make sure data coming in\n> matches what downstream systems expect. Broken schemas = broken pipelines.\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"d76d1be6-303a-4cfd-876b-7a178ecda803"},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Let's see structured vs semi-structured data in Python\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport json\n\n# --- STRUCTURED DATA (like a SQL table / CSV) ---\n# Every row has the exact same shape. Easy to query.\nstructured = pd.DataFrame([\n    {\"user_id\": 1, \"name\": \"Alice\",  \"age\": 28, \"city\": \"Manila\"},\n    {\"user_id\": 2, \"name\": \"Bob\",    \"age\": 34, \"city\": \"Cebu\"},\n    {\"user_id\": 3, \"name\": \"Carlos\", \"age\": 22, \"city\": \"Davao\"},\n])\n\nprint(\"STRUCTURED DATA (clean table):\")\nprint(structured)\nprint(f\"  Shape: {structured.shape}  |  Columns: {list(structured.columns)}\")\n\nprint()\n\n# --- SEMI-STRUCTURED DATA (like a JSON from an API) ---\n# Fields can be nested, missing, or have different shapes per record.\n# Notice: user 2 has no 'phone', user 3 has an extra 'tags' list.\nsemi_structured = [\n    {\"user_id\": 1, \"name\": \"Alice\",  \"contact\": {\"email\": \"alice@example.com\", \"phone\": \"09171234567\"}},\n    {\"user_id\": 2, \"name\": \"Bob\",    \"contact\": {\"email\": \"bob@example.com\"}},  # no phone!\n    {\"user_id\": 3, \"name\": \"Carlos\", \"contact\": {\"email\": \"carlos@example.com\"}, \"tags\": [\"vip\", \"loyal\"]},\n]\n\nprint(\"SEMI-STRUCTURED DATA (raw JSON from API):\")\nfor record in semi_structured:\n    print(f\"  {json.dumps(record)}\")\n\nprint()\nprint(\"Notice: Bob has no 'phone', Carlos has extra 'tags'.\")\nprint(\"A data engineer must handle these inconsistencies!\")","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":2514,"lastExecutedAt":1773720697982,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Let's see structured vs semi-structured data in Python\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport json\n\n# --- STRUCTURED DATA (like a SQL table / CSV) ---\n# Every row has the exact same shape. Easy to query.\nstructured = pd.DataFrame([\n    {\"user_id\": 1, \"name\": \"Alice\",  \"age\": 28, \"city\": \"Manila\"},\n    {\"user_id\": 2, \"name\": \"Bob\",    \"age\": 34, \"city\": \"Cebu\"},\n    {\"user_id\": 3, \"name\": \"Carlos\", \"age\": 22, \"city\": \"Davao\"},\n])\n\nprint(\"STRUCTURED DATA (clean table):\")\nprint(structured)\nprint(f\"  Shape: {structured.shape}  |  Columns: {list(structured.columns)}\")\n\nprint()\n\n# --- SEMI-STRUCTURED DATA (like a JSON from an API) ---\n# Fields can be nested, missing, or have different shapes per record.\n# Notice: user 2 has no 'phone', user 3 has an extra 'tags' list.\nsemi_structured = [\n    {\"user_id\": 1, \"name\": \"Alice\",  \"contact\": {\"email\": \"alice@example.com\", \"phone\": \"09171234567\"}},\n    {\"user_id\": 2, \"name\": \"Bob\",    \"contact\": {\"email\": \"bob@example.com\"}},  # no phone!\n    {\"user_id\": 3, \"name\": \"Carlos\", \"contact\": {\"email\": \"carlos@example.com\"}, \"tags\": [\"vip\", \"loyal\"]},\n]\n\nprint(\"SEMI-STRUCTURED DATA (raw JSON from API):\")\nfor record in semi_structured:\n    print(f\"  {json.dumps(record)}\")\n\nprint()\nprint(\"Notice: Bob has no 'phone', Carlos has extra 'tags'.\")\nprint(\"A data engineer must handle these inconsistencies!\")"},"cell_type":"code","id":"aeb023e8-15a2-4c50-bd48-54cb54d37026","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"STRUCTURED DATA (clean table):\n   user_id    name  age    city\n0        1   Alice   28  Manila\n1        2     Bob   34    Cebu\n2        3  Carlos   22   Davao\n  Shape: (3, 4)  |  Columns: ['user_id', 'name', 'age', 'city']\n\nSEMI-STRUCTURED DATA (raw JSON from API):\n  {\"user_id\": 1, \"name\": \"Alice\", \"contact\": {\"email\": \"alice@example.com\", \"phone\": \"09171234567\"}}\n  {\"user_id\": 2, \"name\": \"Bob\", \"contact\": {\"email\": \"bob@example.com\"}}\n  {\"user_id\": 3, \"name\": \"Carlos\", \"contact\": {\"email\": \"carlos@example.com\"}, \"tags\": [\"vip\", \"loyal\"]}\n\nNotice: Bob has no 'phone', Carlos has extra 'tags'.\nA data engineer must handle these inconsistencies!\n"}],"execution_count":3},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Flattening semi-structured JSON into a structured table\n# This is one of the most common real-world DE tasks!\n# ============================================================\n\nrows = []\nfor record in semi_structured:\n    rows.append({\n        \"user_id\": record[\"user_id\"],\n        \"name\":    record[\"name\"],\n        \"email\":   record[\"contact\"][\"email\"],\n        # .get() returns None if the key doesn't exist — safe!\n        \"phone\":   record[\"contact\"].get(\"phone\", None),\n        # join list into string, or None if no tags\n        \"tags\":    \", \".join(record.get(\"tags\", [])) or None,\n    })\n\ndf_flat = pd.DataFrame(rows)\n\nprint(\"FLATTENED — Semi-structured JSON is now a clean table:\")\nprint(df_flat.to_string(index=False))\nprint()\nprint(\"Missing values (NaN) = fields that didn't exist in the source.\")\nprint(\"This table can now be loaded into a database or data warehouse.\")","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":15,"lastExecutedAt":1773720714379,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Flattening semi-structured JSON into a structured table\n# This is one of the most common real-world DE tasks!\n# ============================================================\n\nrows = []\nfor record in semi_structured:\n    rows.append({\n        \"user_id\": record[\"user_id\"],\n        \"name\":    record[\"name\"],\n        \"email\":   record[\"contact\"][\"email\"],\n        # .get() returns None if the key doesn't exist — safe!\n        \"phone\":   record[\"contact\"].get(\"phone\", None),\n        # join list into string, or None if no tags\n        \"tags\":    \", \".join(record.get(\"tags\", [])) or None,\n    })\n\ndf_flat = pd.DataFrame(rows)\n\nprint(\"FLATTENED — Semi-structured JSON is now a clean table:\")\nprint(df_flat.to_string(index=False))\nprint()\nprint(\"Missing values (NaN) = fields that didn't exist in the source.\")\nprint(\"This table can now be loaded into a database or data warehouse.\")"},"cell_type":"code","id":"7b63878c-f825-4f40-a662-7f3b5e8f6780","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"FLATTENED — Semi-structured JSON is now a clean table:\n user_id   name              email       phone       tags\n       1  Alice  alice@example.com 09171234567       None\n       2    Bob    bob@example.com        None       None\n       3 Carlos carlos@example.com        None vip, loyal\n\nMissing values (NaN) = fields that didn't exist in the source.\nThis table can now be loaded into a database or data warehouse.\n"}],"execution_count":4},{"source":"---\n# 4. Data Pipelines — The Heart of Data Engineering\n\n## What IS a pipeline, really?\n\nA **pipeline** is just a series of steps that run automatically, one after another.\nThink of it like a car assembly line:\n\n```\n🏭 Car Factory Assembly Line:\n  [Steel arrives] → [Cut to shape] → [Welded together] → [Painted] → [Final car] ✅\n\n🗂️ Data Pipeline:\n  [Raw data in] → [Validated] → [Cleaned] → [Transformed] → [Stored & ready] ✅\n```\n\nEach step is called a **task** or **stage**. If one step fails, the rest don't run\n(just like a broken weld means the car doesn't get painted).\n\n---\n\n## The 3 stages of every pipeline: Ingest → Transform → Serve\n\n### Stage 1 — INGEST (\"Get the data\")\nPull data from where it lives: a database, an API, a file upload, a Kafka stream.\nAt this stage, we store the **raw data as-is** — we don't modify it yet.\nWhy? Because if something goes wrong in transformation, we can always re-process from raw.\n\n### Stage 2 — TRANSFORM (\"Clean and shape the data\")\nThis is where most of the engineering work happens:\n- Remove duplicates\n- Fix or flag missing values\n- Standardize formats (e.g., all dates in YYYY-MM-DD)\n- Join multiple datasets together\n- Calculate new fields (e.g., `revenue = quantity * price`)\n\n### Stage 3 — SERVE (\"Make it available\")\nLoad the clean data into the final destination:\n- A data warehouse (for analysts to query)\n- A dashboard (for business users to view)\n- A feature store (for ML models to use)\n- Back to an application database (for the product)\n\n---\n\n## Important pipeline properties\n\n### 🔁 Idempotency — \"Running it twice gives the same result\"\nIf your pipeline runs at midnight but crashes at 11:59pm, you need to re-run it.\nAn idempotent pipeline won't create duplicate records — it'll just overwrite or skip.\n\n```python\n# BAD: Running twice creates duplicates!\nINSERT INTO sales SELECT * FROM raw_sales\n\n# GOOD: Running twice is safe — it replaces the data\nINSERT OR REPLACE INTO sales SELECT * FROM raw_sales\n-- or use MERGE / UPSERT logic\n```\n\n### ⏪ Backfilling — \"Reprocessing old data\"\nImagine you find a bug in your transformation logic.\nYou fix it — but the last 6 months of data was processed with the buggy code!\n**Backfilling** = re-running the pipeline on historical data to correct it.\n\n### 🔔 Monitoring — \"Know when something breaks\"\nPipelines fail. Always. Good engineers set up:\n- Alerts when a pipeline doesn't complete on time\n- Alerts when data volumes are unexpectedly low (maybe source went down)\n- Alerts when data quality checks fail\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"59bac3d2-ca03-4c56-a305-c981f1b311ea"},{"source":"---\n# 5. ETL vs ELT — Classic vs Modern Approach\n\nBoth describe the ORDER of steps in a pipeline. The difference is\n**where** the transformation happens.\n\n---\n\n## 🏛️ ETL — Extract → Transform → Load (the classic way)\n\nTransform the data **BEFORE** loading it into the warehouse.\n\n```\n[Source DB] ──► EXTRACT ──► TRANSFORM ──► LOAD ──► [Warehouse]\n                  (pull)    (on a server)  (insert)  (clean data only)\n```\n\n**Imagine it like this:** You're moving to a new house.\nBefore packing boxes, you declutter — throw out everything you don't need.\nOnly clean, useful things get moved.\n\n**Good for:**\n- When you absolutely cannot store raw/sensitive data (e.g., hospitals with patient records)\n- Legacy systems where storage is expensive\n- When transformation is simple and fast\n\n**Drawback:** If you later realize you needed something you threw out — it's gone.\n\n---\n\n## ☁️ ELT — Extract → Load → Transform (the modern way)\n\nLoad the raw data FIRST, transform it INSIDE the warehouse.\n\n```\n[Source DB] ──► EXTRACT ──► LOAD ──► [Warehouse] ──► TRANSFORM\n                  (pull)   (insert)   (raw + clean)   (using SQL / dbt)\n```\n\n**Same house analogy:** Move EVERYTHING first, then sort and organize once you're in the new house.\nYou have all your original stuff available if you need it.\n\n**Good for:**\n- Cloud warehouses like BigQuery/Snowflake (cheap storage, powerful compute)\n- When you want to keep raw data for future re-processing\n- When transformation logic changes often\n\n**Drawback:** Your warehouse contains messy raw data — needs good organization.\n\n---\n\n## Which one is used today?\n\n**ELT dominates modern data stacks.** Here's why:\n- Cloud storage is cheap (storing raw data costs almost nothing)\n- Tools like **dbt** make transforming data inside the warehouse very easy\n- You never lose your raw data\n\n```\nModern Data Stack (ELT):\n──────────────────────────\nFivetran / Airbyte  →  Snowflake / BigQuery  →  dbt  →  Dashboard\n(Extract + Load)       (Store raw data)          (Transform)\n```\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"a0360f0f-1403-4da0-b162-b5a5801afd77"},{"source":"---\n# 6. Where Data Lives — Storage Types Explained\n\nNot all databases are created equal. The type of storage you choose\nhas a huge impact on **query speed, cost, and what you can do with the data**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔷 OLTP Databases — Built for Applications\n\n**OLTP** = Online Transaction Processing\n\nThese power the apps users interact with. Designed for:\n- Many small, fast read/write operations\n- One record at a time\n- Immediate consistency (if you book a seat, nobody else can book it)\n\n```\nExamples: PostgreSQL, MySQL, MongoDB, SQLite\n\nTypical query:\n  SELECT * FROM users WHERE user_id = 12345;  -- get ONE user\n  UPDATE cart SET quantity = 2 WHERE item_id = 99;  -- update ONE row\n```\n\n**Analogy:** A cash register. Fast at ringing up one item. Not designed to\nanalyze all receipts from the last 5 years.\n\n---\n\n## 🔷 Data Warehouse — Built for Analytics\n\n**OLAP** = Online Analytical Processing\n\nDesigned for analytical queries across **millions or billions of rows**.\nOptimized for reads, not writes.\n\n```\nExamples: Snowflake, BigQuery, Amazon Redshift, DuckDB\n\nTypical query:\n  SELECT region, SUM(revenue), COUNT(DISTINCT customer_id)\n  FROM orders\n  WHERE order_date >= '2024-01-01'\n  GROUP BY region;\n  -- Scanning MILLIONS of rows in seconds!\n```\n\n**Analogy:** The accounting department. They have all historical records and\ncan produce any financial report — but they're not the ones ringing up customers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔷 Data Lake — Store Everything, Sort Later\n\nA **data lake** is a massive, cheap storage bucket that holds ALL your data\nin its **raw form** — structured, semi-structured, unstructured.\n\n```\nExamples: AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, Azure Data Lake\n\nWhat lives in a data lake:\n  /raw/\n    /orders/2024/01/01/orders.parquet\n    /clickstream/2024/01/01/events.json\n    /support_tickets/2024/01/01/tickets.csv\n    /images/product_photos/*.jpg\n```\n\n**Analogy:** A giant warehouse where you dump everything.\nSuper cheap, but you need a map to find anything.\nWithout good organization, it becomes a **\"data swamp\"**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔷 Data Lakehouse — Best of Both Worlds\n\nThe newest evolution: cheap lake storage + warehouse query performance.\n\n```\nFormats: Delta Lake (Databricks), Apache Iceberg, Apache Hudi\n\nWhat it gives you:\n  ✅ Store data cheaply (like a lake, on S3/GCS)\n  ✅ Query it fast with SQL (like a warehouse)\n  ✅ ACID transactions (like a database — no partial/corrupt writes)\n  ✅ Time travel (query data as it looked 30 days ago!)\n```\n\n| | OLTP DB | Warehouse | Lake | Lakehouse |\n|--|:-------:|:---------:|:----:|:---------:|\n| Fast transactions | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |\n| Analytical queries | ❌ | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ |\n| Any data format | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ |\n| Very cheap storage | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ |\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"334c51c0-9ff2-47c1-b07a-209c50a893f3"},{"source":"---\n# 7. Data Formats — Why Not Just Use CSV for Everything?\n\nGreat question! A lot of beginners ask this. The short answer:\n**CSV is fine for small files, but terrible at scale.**\n\nLet's understand why by looking at how each format works.\n\n---\n\n## 📄 CSV — The classic, universal format\n\n```csv\norder_id,product,amount,date\n1001,Laptop,55000,2024-01-15\n1002,Mouse,750,2024-01-16\n```\n\n✅ Human-readable. Opens in Excel. Every tool supports it.  \n❌ No data types (everything is a string — is `55000` a number or text?)  \n❌ No compression — a 1GB CSV stays 1GB  \n❌ To find the `amount` column, you must read EVERY column in every row  \n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Parquet — The data engineer's best friend\n\nParquet stores data **by column**, not by row. This is revolutionary for analytics.\n\n```\nCSV (row-based):              Parquet (column-based):\n─────────────────             ──────────────────────\n1001 | Laptop | 55000         order_id column: [1001, 1002, 1003, ...]\n1002 | Mouse  | 750           product column:  [Laptop, Mouse, Keyboard, ...]\n1003 | KB     | 2500          amount column:   [55000, 750, 2500, ...]\n\nQuery: \"What is the total amount?\"\nCSV:     Must read ALL columns for ALL rows just to get 'amount'\nParquet: Read ONLY the 'amount' column — skip everything else!\n```\n\nResult: Parquet queries on 1 billion rows can be **10-100x faster** than CSV.\nPlus, Parquet compresses by up to 80%. A 10GB CSV might be 2GB in Parquet.\n\n---\n\n## 🔀 Avro — The streaming format\n\nAvro stores the **schema inside the file itself**. This makes it perfect for Kafka:\nwhen you send a message, the receiver always knows what fields to expect,\neven if the schema changed.\n\n---\n\n## When to use which:\n\n| Situation | Use |\n|-----------|-----|\n| Sharing data with a non-technical team | CSV |\n| Storing data in a data lake for analytics | **Parquet** |\n| Sending events through Kafka | Avro |\n| Hive / Hadoop environment | ORC |\n| REST API responses | JSON |\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"e07e6fbb-ff7c-4b5f-8ded-3bc1549e232f"},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Let's see the size difference between CSV and Parquet\n# We'll generate 100,000 rows and compare file sizes\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nimport os\n\n# Generate a realistic dataset with 100,000 rows\nnp.random.seed(42)\nn = 100_000\n\nproducts  = [\"Laptop\", \"Mouse\", \"Keyboard\", \"Monitor\", \"Headset\", \"Webcam\"]\nstatuses  = [\"completed\", \"pending\", \"shipped\", \"cancelled\"]\nregions   = [\"NCR\", \"Region III\", \"Region IV-A\", \"Region VII\", \"Region XI\"]\n\ndf = pd.DataFrame({\n    \"order_id\":   range(1, n + 1),\n    \"user_id\":    np.random.randint(1000, 9999, n),\n    \"product\":    np.random.choice(products, n),\n    \"amount\":     np.random.uniform(100, 80000, n).round(2),\n    \"quantity\":   np.random.randint(1, 10, n),\n    \"region\":     np.random.choice(regions, n),\n    \"status\":     np.random.choice(statuses, n),\n    \"order_date\": pd.date_range(\"2024-01-01\", periods=n, freq=\"1min\"),\n})\n\nprint(f\"Dataset: {n:,} rows x {df.shape[1]} columns\")\nprint(df.head(3).to_string(index=False))\nprint()\n\n# Save as CSV\ndf.to_csv(\"/tmp/orders.csv\", index=False)\ncsv_size = os.path.getsize(\"/tmp/orders.csv\") / 1024 / 1024\n\n# Save as Parquet\ndf.to_parquet(\"/tmp/orders.parquet\", index=False)\nparquet_size = os.path.getsize(\"/tmp/orders.parquet\") / 1024 / 1024\n\nprint(\"FILE SIZE COMPARISON:\")\nprint(f\"  CSV     file: {csv_size:.2f} MB\")\nprint(f\"  Parquet file: {parquet_size:.2f} MB\")\nprint(f\"  Parquet is {csv_size / parquet_size:.1f}x smaller than CSV!\")","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":434,"lastExecutedAt":1773720796832,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Let's see the size difference between CSV and Parquet\n# We'll generate 100,000 rows and compare file sizes\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nimport os\n\n# Generate a realistic dataset with 100,000 rows\nnp.random.seed(42)\nn = 100_000\n\nproducts  = [\"Laptop\", \"Mouse\", \"Keyboard\", \"Monitor\", \"Headset\", \"Webcam\"]\nstatuses  = [\"completed\", \"pending\", \"shipped\", \"cancelled\"]\nregions   = [\"NCR\", \"Region III\", \"Region IV-A\", \"Region VII\", \"Region XI\"]\n\ndf = pd.DataFrame({\n    \"order_id\":   range(1, n + 1),\n    \"user_id\":    np.random.randint(1000, 9999, n),\n    \"product\":    np.random.choice(products, n),\n    \"amount\":     np.random.uniform(100, 80000, n).round(2),\n    \"quantity\":   np.random.randint(1, 10, n),\n    \"region\":     np.random.choice(regions, n),\n    \"status\":     np.random.choice(statuses, n),\n    \"order_date\": pd.date_range(\"2024-01-01\", periods=n, freq=\"1min\"),\n})\n\nprint(f\"Dataset: {n:,} rows x {df.shape[1]} columns\")\nprint(df.head(3).to_string(index=False))\nprint()\n\n# Save as CSV\ndf.to_csv(\"/tmp/orders.csv\", index=False)\ncsv_size = os.path.getsize(\"/tmp/orders.csv\") / 1024 / 1024\n\n# Save as Parquet\ndf.to_parquet(\"/tmp/orders.parquet\", index=False)\nparquet_size = os.path.getsize(\"/tmp/orders.parquet\") / 1024 / 1024\n\nprint(\"FILE SIZE COMPARISON:\")\nprint(f\"  CSV     file: {csv_size:.2f} MB\")\nprint(f\"  Parquet file: {parquet_size:.2f} MB\")\nprint(f\"  Parquet is {csv_size / parquet_size:.1f}x smaller than CSV!\")"},"cell_type":"code","id":"2b477860-f7a6-445a-bbba-b223ae09f622","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"Dataset: 100,000 rows x 8 columns\n order_id  user_id product   amount  quantity     region    status          order_date\n        1     8270   Mouse 29128.74         8  Region XI   pending 2024-01-01 00:00:00\n        2     1860  Webcam  2863.06         7 Region VII completed 2024-01-01 00:01:00\n        3     6390  Webcam 25284.54         2        NCR   pending 2024-01-01 00:02:00\n\nFILE SIZE COMPARISON:\n  CSV     file: 6.46 MB\n  Parquet file: 2.46 MB\n  Parquet is 2.6x smaller than CSV!\n"}],"execution_count":5},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Now let's compare QUERY SPEED: reading just one column\n# This simulates: SELECT SUM(amount) FROM orders\n# ============================================================\n\nimport time\n\n# Reading the full CSV (must read ALL columns)\nstart = time.time()\ndf_csv = pd.read_csv(\"/tmp/orders.csv\", usecols=[\"amount\"])\ncsv_time = time.time() - start\ncsv_total = df_csv[\"amount\"].sum()\n\n# Reading only the 'amount' column from Parquet (skips all other columns!)\nstart = time.time()\ndf_parquet = pd.read_parquet(\"/tmp/orders.parquet\", columns=[\"amount\"])\nparquet_time = time.time() - start\nparquet_total = df_parquet[\"amount\"].sum()\n\nprint(\"QUERY: SUM of 'amount' column across 100,000 rows\")\nprint(f\"  CSV     time: {csv_time:.4f}s  |  result: ${csv_total:,.2f}\")\nprint(f\"  Parquet time: {parquet_time:.4f}s  |  result: ${parquet_total:,.2f}\")\nprint()\nif parquet_time > 0:\n    speedup = csv_time / parquet_time\n    print(f\"  Parquet is ~{speedup:.1f}x faster for this column-scan query!\")\nprint()\nprint(\"At 1 BILLION rows, this difference becomes minutes vs hours.\")\nprint(\"THIS is why data engineers use Parquet instead of CSV.\")","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":63,"lastExecutedAt":1773720811590,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Now let's compare QUERY SPEED: reading just one column\n# This simulates: SELECT SUM(amount) FROM orders\n# ============================================================\n\nimport time\n\n# Reading the full CSV (must read ALL columns)\nstart = time.time()\ndf_csv = pd.read_csv(\"/tmp/orders.csv\", usecols=[\"amount\"])\ncsv_time = time.time() - start\ncsv_total = df_csv[\"amount\"].sum()\n\n# Reading only the 'amount' column from Parquet (skips all other columns!)\nstart = time.time()\ndf_parquet = pd.read_parquet(\"/tmp/orders.parquet\", columns=[\"amount\"])\nparquet_time = time.time() - start\nparquet_total = df_parquet[\"amount\"].sum()\n\nprint(\"QUERY: SUM of 'amount' column across 100,000 rows\")\nprint(f\"  CSV     time: {csv_time:.4f}s  |  result: ${csv_total:,.2f}\")\nprint(f\"  Parquet time: {parquet_time:.4f}s  |  result: ${parquet_total:,.2f}\")\nprint()\nif parquet_time > 0:\n    speedup = csv_time / parquet_time\n    print(f\"  Parquet is ~{speedup:.1f}x faster for this column-scan query!\")\nprint()\nprint(\"At 1 BILLION rows, this difference becomes minutes vs hours.\")\nprint(\"THIS is why data engineers use Parquet instead of CSV.\")"},"cell_type":"code","id":"100eee2b-726b-420f-a117-a6a8af92cfc9","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"QUERY: SUM of 'amount' column across 100,000 rows\n  CSV     time: 0.0363s  |  result: $4,008,680,885.13\n  Parquet time: 0.0152s  |  result: $4,008,680,885.13\n\n  Parquet is ~2.4x faster for this column-scan query!\n\nAt 1 BILLION rows, this difference becomes minutes vs hours.\nTHIS is why data engineers use Parquet instead of CSV.\n"}],"execution_count":6},{"source":"---\n# 8. The Modern Data Engineering Tool Stack\n\nThere are hundreds of tools in the DE ecosystem. Let's cut through the noise\nand understand what each **category** of tool does — and which specific tools matter.\n\n---\n\n## The 5 layers of the modern data stack\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  LAYER 5: BI / CONSUMPTION                                  │\n│  Tools: Tableau, Looker, Power BI, Metabase                 │\n│  \"Show me the data in charts and dashboards\"                │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  LAYER 4: TRANSFORMATION                                    │\n│  Tools: dbt, Apache Spark, Pandas                           │\n│  \"Clean, join, and model the data inside the warehouse\"     │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  LAYER 3: STORAGE                                           │\n│  Tools: Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift, S3 + Delta Lake      │\n│  \"Where does all this data live?\"                           │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  LAYER 2: INGESTION                                         │\n│  Tools: Fivetran, Airbyte, Kafka, custom Python scripts     │\n│  \"How do we get data FROM the sources INTO storage?\"        │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  LAYER 1: SOURCES                                           │\n│  Production DBs, SaaS apps (Salesforce, Stripe), APIs, IoT  │\n│  \"Where does the raw data actually come from?\"              │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n---\n\n## 🎛️ Bonus Layer: Orchestration\n\n**Orchestration** is the glue that runs and schedules all the above layers.\nYou tell it: *\"Run this pipeline every day at midnight. If it fails, retry 3 times, then alert me.\"*\n\n```\nApache Airflow (industry standard):\n  You define a DAG — Directed Acyclic Graph — a visual flowchart of tasks.\n\n  Task A  ──►  Task B  ──►  Task D  ──►  Task F (done)\n               Task C  ──►  Task E  ──►  Task F\n\n  Tasks can run in parallel, wait for each other, and retry on failure.\n```\n\n---\n\n## What should a beginner learn FIRST?\n\n```\nWEEK 1-4:    SQL (the most important skill in DE)\nWEEK 5-8:    Python + Pandas (data manipulation)\nWEEK 9-12:   Build ETL pipelines in Python (no fancy tools yet)\nMONTH 4:     dbt (SQL transformations the right way)\nMONTH 5:     Apache Airflow (schedule your pipelines)\nMONTH 6:     Cloud (BigQuery or Snowflake + S3/GCS)\nMONTH 7+:    Spark, Kafka, advanced topics\n```\n\n> 💡 Don't try to learn Spark before you've built a real pipeline in Python.\n> The tools are useless without understanding the underlying concepts first.\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"723a390a-616a-4782-93a6-6ae3f571e56e"},{"source":"---\n# 9. Data Quality — \"Garbage In, Garbage Out\"\n\n## Why is this so important?\n\nHere's a real scenario:\n\n> A company trains a machine learning model to predict which customers will churn.\n> The model says 30% of customers will leave next month.\n> The retention team calls all 30% and offers discounts. It costs \\$500,000.\n> Turns out — the model was trained on dirty data. A bug caused 20% of customers\n> to be counted twice. The real churn rate was 15%. They spent double what was needed.\n\n**Bad data quality = wrong decisions = real business damage.**\n\n---\n\n## The 6 Dimensions of Data Quality\n\n### 1. ✅ Completeness — \"Is anything missing?\"\nAre there NULL values where there shouldn't be?\nExample: An order with no `user_id` — who placed this order?\n\n### 2. 🎯 Accuracy — \"Is it correct?\"\nDoes the data reflect reality?\nExample: `age = 250` — clearly wrong. `order_amount = -500` — suspicious.\n\n### 3. 🔁 Uniqueness — \"Are there duplicates?\"\nDoes each row represent exactly one thing?\nExample: The same order appearing twice because the ETL ran twice.\n\n### 4. 📏 Consistency — \"Does it match across systems?\"\nExample: The CRM says customer Alice has 50 orders.\nThe warehouse says she has 48. Which is right?\n\n### 5. ⏰ Timeliness — \"Is it fresh?\"\nIs the data recent enough to be useful?\nExample: Making decisions based on yesterday's inventory when it changes by the hour.\n\n### 6. 📐 Validity — \"Does it follow the rules?\"\nDoes the data match the expected format or range?\nExample: `email = \"not-an-email\"`, `date = \"13/25/2024\"` (month 13 doesn't exist)\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"448ad60b-efd7-4925-956c-630b187ece24"},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Comprehensive Data Quality Check — Real-world style\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport io\n\n# This is realistic messy data you'd actually encounter\nmessy_data = \"\"\"order_id,user_id,email,product,amount,quantity,order_date,status\n1001,201,alice@example.com,Laptop,55000,1,2024-01-15,completed\n1002,202,bob-not-an-email,Mouse,750,2,2024-01-16,completed\n1003,203,carlos@example.com,Keyboard,,1,2024-01-17,pending\n1004,201,alice@example.com,Monitor,12000,1,2024-01-18,completed\n1004,201,alice@example.com,Monitor,12000,1,2024-01-18,completed\n1005,204,diana@example.com,Webcam,-500,1,2024-01-19,completed\n1006,205,eve@example.com,Headset,3200,0,2024-01-20,shipped\n1007,206,frank@example.com,Laptop,55000,250,13/25/2024,completed\n1008,,grace@example.com,Mouse,800,1,2024-01-22,completed\n\"\"\"\n\ndf = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(messy_data))\nprint(\"RAW DATA:\")\nprint(df.to_string(index=False))\nprint()","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":63,"lastExecutedAt":1773720864996,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Comprehensive Data Quality Check — Real-world style\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport io\n\n# This is realistic messy data you'd actually encounter\nmessy_data = \"\"\"order_id,user_id,email,product,amount,quantity,order_date,status\n1001,201,alice@example.com,Laptop,55000,1,2024-01-15,completed\n1002,202,bob-not-an-email,Mouse,750,2,2024-01-16,completed\n1003,203,carlos@example.com,Keyboard,,1,2024-01-17,pending\n1004,201,alice@example.com,Monitor,12000,1,2024-01-18,completed\n1004,201,alice@example.com,Monitor,12000,1,2024-01-18,completed\n1005,204,diana@example.com,Webcam,-500,1,2024-01-19,completed\n1006,205,eve@example.com,Headset,3200,0,2024-01-20,shipped\n1007,206,frank@example.com,Laptop,55000,250,13/25/2024,completed\n1008,,grace@example.com,Mouse,800,1,2024-01-22,completed\n\"\"\"\n\ndf = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(messy_data))\nprint(\"RAW DATA:\")\nprint(df.to_string(index=False))\nprint()"},"cell_type":"code","id":"87d80805-cf2b-4f02-bca8-4da66e6ba692","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"RAW DATA:\n order_id  user_id              email  product  amount  quantity order_date    status\n     1001    201.0  alice@example.com   Laptop 55000.0         1 2024-01-15 completed\n     1002    202.0   bob-not-an-email    Mouse   750.0         2 2024-01-16 completed\n     1003    203.0 carlos@example.com Keyboard     NaN         1 2024-01-17   pending\n     1004    201.0  alice@example.com  Monitor 12000.0         1 2024-01-18 completed\n     1004    201.0  alice@example.com  Monitor 12000.0         1 2024-01-18 completed\n     1005    204.0  diana@example.com   Webcam  -500.0         1 2024-01-19 completed\n     1006    205.0    eve@example.com  Headset  3200.0         0 2024-01-20   shipped\n     1007    206.0  frank@example.com   Laptop 55000.0       250 13/25/2024 completed\n     1008      NaN  grace@example.com    Mouse   800.0         1 2024-01-22 completed\n\n"}],"execution_count":7},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Run quality checks and flag issues — don't silently drop!\n# Good DE practice: flag issues so you can investigate them\n# ============================================================\n\nimport re\n\nissues = []\n\n# 1. COMPLETENESS — missing required fields\nrequired_cols = [\"order_id\", \"user_id\", \"amount\"]\nfor col in required_cols:\n    missing_rows = df[df[col].isna()].index.tolist()\n    for row in missing_rows:\n        issues.append({\"row\": row+2, \"check\": \"COMPLETENESS\",\n                       \"field\": col, \"value\": None,\n                       \"message\": f\"Required field '{col}' is missing\"})\n\n# 2. UNIQUENESS — duplicate order IDs\ndupes = df[df.duplicated(subset=[\"order_id\"], keep=False)]\nfor _, row in dupes.iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"UNIQUENESS\",\n                   \"field\": \"order_id\", \"value\": row[\"order_id\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Duplicate order_id: {row['order_id']}\"})\n\n# 3. ACCURACY — negative amounts\nfor _, row in df[df[\"amount\"] < 0].iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"ACCURACY\",\n                   \"field\": \"amount\", \"value\": row[\"amount\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Negative amount: {row['amount']}\"})\n\n# 4. ACCURACY — zero or unreasonable quantity\nfor _, row in df[(df[\"quantity\"] <= 0) | (df[\"quantity\"] > 100)].iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"ACCURACY\",\n                   \"field\": \"quantity\", \"value\": row[\"quantity\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Suspicious quantity: {row['quantity']}\"})\n\n# 5. VALIDITY — email format check\nemail_pattern = r'^[\\w.-]+@[\\w.-]+\\.\\w+$'\nfor _, row in df[~df[\"email\"].str.match(email_pattern, na=False)].iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"VALIDITY\",\n                   \"field\": \"email\", \"value\": row[\"email\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Invalid email format: {row['email']}\"})\n\n# 6. VALIDITY — date format check\nfor _, row in df.iterrows():\n    try:\n        pd.to_datetime(row[\"order_date\"], format=\"%Y-%m-%d\")\n    except:\n        issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"VALIDITY\",\n                       \"field\": \"order_date\", \"value\": row[\"order_date\"],\n                       \"message\": f\"Invalid date format: {row['order_date']}\"})\n\n# Print the quality report\nprint(\"DATA QUALITY REPORT\")\nprint(\"=\" * 65)\nif not issues:\n    print(\"  No issues found!\")\nelse:\n    for i in issues:\n        print(f\"  Row {i['row']:>2} | [{i['check']:<15}] {i['message']}\")\n\nprint(\"=\" * 65)\nprint(f\"  Total issues found: {len(issues)} across {df.shape[0]} rows\")\nprint(f\"  Rows with at least one issue: ~{len(set(i['row'] for i in issues))}\")","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":61,"lastExecutedAt":1773720881056,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Run quality checks and flag issues — don't silently drop!\n# Good DE practice: flag issues so you can investigate them\n# ============================================================\n\nimport re\n\nissues = []\n\n# 1. COMPLETENESS — missing required fields\nrequired_cols = [\"order_id\", \"user_id\", \"amount\"]\nfor col in required_cols:\n    missing_rows = df[df[col].isna()].index.tolist()\n    for row in missing_rows:\n        issues.append({\"row\": row+2, \"check\": \"COMPLETENESS\",\n                       \"field\": col, \"value\": None,\n                       \"message\": f\"Required field '{col}' is missing\"})\n\n# 2. UNIQUENESS — duplicate order IDs\ndupes = df[df.duplicated(subset=[\"order_id\"], keep=False)]\nfor _, row in dupes.iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"UNIQUENESS\",\n                   \"field\": \"order_id\", \"value\": row[\"order_id\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Duplicate order_id: {row['order_id']}\"})\n\n# 3. ACCURACY — negative amounts\nfor _, row in df[df[\"amount\"] < 0].iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"ACCURACY\",\n                   \"field\": \"amount\", \"value\": row[\"amount\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Negative amount: {row['amount']}\"})\n\n# 4. ACCURACY — zero or unreasonable quantity\nfor _, row in df[(df[\"quantity\"] <= 0) | (df[\"quantity\"] > 100)].iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"ACCURACY\",\n                   \"field\": \"quantity\", \"value\": row[\"quantity\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Suspicious quantity: {row['quantity']}\"})\n\n# 5. VALIDITY — email format check\nemail_pattern = r'^[\\w.-]+@[\\w.-]+\\.\\w+$'\nfor _, row in df[~df[\"email\"].str.match(email_pattern, na=False)].iterrows():\n    issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"VALIDITY\",\n                   \"field\": \"email\", \"value\": row[\"email\"],\n                   \"message\": f\"Invalid email format: {row['email']}\"})\n\n# 6. VALIDITY — date format check\nfor _, row in df.iterrows():\n    try:\n        pd.to_datetime(row[\"order_date\"], format=\"%Y-%m-%d\")\n    except:\n        issues.append({\"row\": row.name+2, \"check\": \"VALIDITY\",\n                       \"field\": \"order_date\", \"value\": row[\"order_date\"],\n                       \"message\": f\"Invalid date format: {row['order_date']}\"})\n\n# Print the quality report\nprint(\"DATA QUALITY REPORT\")\nprint(\"=\" * 65)\nif not issues:\n    print(\"  No issues found!\")\nelse:\n    for i in issues:\n        print(f\"  Row {i['row']:>2} | [{i['check']:<15}] {i['message']}\")\n\nprint(\"=\" * 65)\nprint(f\"  Total issues found: {len(issues)} across {df.shape[0]} rows\")\nprint(f\"  Rows with at least one issue: ~{len(set(i['row'] for i in issues))}\")"},"cell_type":"code","id":"b48f82c5-2d7b-4643-b07a-ddc6de4f2ce5","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"DATA QUALITY REPORT\n=================================================================\n  Row 10 | [COMPLETENESS   ] Required field 'user_id' is missing\n  Row  4 | [COMPLETENESS   ] Required field 'amount' is missing\n  Row  5 | [UNIQUENESS     ] Duplicate order_id: 1004\n  Row  6 | [UNIQUENESS     ] Duplicate order_id: 1004\n  Row  7 | [ACCURACY       ] Negative amount: -500.0\n  Row  8 | [ACCURACY       ] Suspicious quantity: 0\n  Row  9 | [ACCURACY       ] Suspicious quantity: 250\n  Row  3 | [VALIDITY       ] Invalid email format: bob-not-an-email\n  Row  9 | [VALIDITY       ] Invalid date format: 13/25/2024\n=================================================================\n  Total issues found: 9 across 9 rows\n  Rows with at least one issue: ~8\n"}],"execution_count":8},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Fix what we can, quarantine what we can't\n# Real-world: don't just drop bad data silently!\n# ============================================================\n\n# Identify bad rows (ones we can't safely fix)\nbad_order_ids = set(r[\"value\"] for r in issues if r[\"check\"] == \"UNIQUENESS\")\n\n# Quarantine: set aside rows we can't fix, for manual review\nquarantine_mask = (\n    df[\"user_id\"].isna() |                          # missing user\n    df[\"amount\"].isna() |                           # missing amount\n    (df[\"amount\"] < 0) |                            # negative amount\n    df.duplicated(subset=[\"order_id\"], keep=\"first\") # second occurrence of duplicate\n)\n\ndf_quarantine = df[quarantine_mask].copy()\ndf_clean = df[~quarantine_mask].copy()\n\n# Fix what we can on the clean subset\ndf_clean[\"order_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean[\"order_date\"], errors=\"coerce\")\ndf_clean[\"quantity\"] = df_clean[\"quantity\"].clip(lower=1, upper=100)  # cap at 100\n\nprint(f\"Original rows:    {len(df)}\")\nprint(f\"Clean rows:       {len(df_clean)}  ← sent to warehouse\")\nprint(f\"Quarantine rows:  {len(df_quarantine)}  ← sent to review queue\")\nprint()\nprint(\"CLEAN DATA (ready for warehouse):\")\nprint(df_clean[[\"order_id\",\"user_id\",\"product\",\"amount\",\"quantity\",\"order_date\"]].to_string(index=False))\nprint()\nprint(\"QUARANTINED DATA (needs manual review):\")\nprint(df_quarantine[[\"order_id\",\"user_id\",\"product\",\"amount\"]].to_string(index=False))","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":20,"lastExecutedAt":1773720896556,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Fix what we can, quarantine what we can't\n# Real-world: don't just drop bad data silently!\n# ============================================================\n\n# Identify bad rows (ones we can't safely fix)\nbad_order_ids = set(r[\"value\"] for r in issues if r[\"check\"] == \"UNIQUENESS\")\n\n# Quarantine: set aside rows we can't fix, for manual review\nquarantine_mask = (\n    df[\"user_id\"].isna() |                          # missing user\n    df[\"amount\"].isna() |                           # missing amount\n    (df[\"amount\"] < 0) |                            # negative amount\n    df.duplicated(subset=[\"order_id\"], keep=\"first\") # second occurrence of duplicate\n)\n\ndf_quarantine = df[quarantine_mask].copy()\ndf_clean = df[~quarantine_mask].copy()\n\n# Fix what we can on the clean subset\ndf_clean[\"order_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean[\"order_date\"], errors=\"coerce\")\ndf_clean[\"quantity\"] = df_clean[\"quantity\"].clip(lower=1, upper=100)  # cap at 100\n\nprint(f\"Original rows:    {len(df)}\")\nprint(f\"Clean rows:       {len(df_clean)}  ← sent to warehouse\")\nprint(f\"Quarantine rows:  {len(df_quarantine)}  ← sent to review queue\")\nprint()\nprint(\"CLEAN DATA (ready for warehouse):\")\nprint(df_clean[[\"order_id\",\"user_id\",\"product\",\"amount\",\"quantity\",\"order_date\"]].to_string(index=False))\nprint()\nprint(\"QUARANTINED DATA (needs manual review):\")\nprint(df_quarantine[[\"order_id\",\"user_id\",\"product\",\"amount\"]].to_string(index=False))"},"cell_type":"code","id":"2e60cdc7-c4ff-4fbd-bc33-cd94142aec20","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"Original rows:    9\nClean rows:       5  ← sent to warehouse\nQuarantine rows:  4  ← sent to review queue\n\nCLEAN DATA (ready for warehouse):\n order_id  user_id product  amount  quantity order_date\n     1001    201.0  Laptop 55000.0         1 2024-01-15\n     1002    202.0   Mouse   750.0         2 2024-01-16\n     1004    201.0 Monitor 12000.0         1 2024-01-18\n     1006    205.0 Headset  3200.0         1 2024-01-20\n     1007    206.0  Laptop 55000.0       100        NaT\n\nQUARANTINED DATA (needs manual review):\n order_id  user_id  product  amount\n     1003    203.0 Keyboard     NaN\n     1004    201.0  Monitor 12000.0\n     1005    204.0   Webcam  -500.0\n     1008      NaN    Mouse   800.0\n"}],"execution_count":9},{"source":"---\n# 10. Building a Real Mini Pipeline From Scratch\n\nNow let's put **everything together** and build a proper, production-style ETL pipeline.\n\nWe'll simulate a real scenario:\n> \"Every night at midnight, pull today's orders from our database,\n> clean and validate them, enrich them with product info,\n> and load them into the data warehouse.\"\n\n## Architecture of what we're building:\n\n```\n  [Orders DB]  ──►  extract()  ──►  validate()  ──►  transform()\n                                                          │\n  [Products DB] ──► extract()  ──────────────────────────┘\n                                                          │\n                                                       load()  ──►  [Warehouse]\n                                                          │\n                                                     report()  ──►  [Logs / Alerts]\n```\n\nEach step is a **pure function** — it takes data in, returns data out.\nThis makes them easy to test individually.\n","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","id":"6e0e7d9a-ded3-4a13-8ad4-02617ce08696"},{"source":"# ============================================================\n# Full Production-Style ETL Pipeline\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport io\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\n# ── Simulated source data ────────────────────────────────────\n\nORDERS_SOURCE = \"\"\"order_id,user_id,product_id,quantity,order_date,status\n2001,301,P001,1,2024-06-01,completed\n2002,302,P003,2,2024-06-01,completed\n2003,303,P002,1,2024-06-01,pending\n2004,301,P001,1,2024-06-01,completed\n2004,301,P001,1,2024-06-01,completed\n2005,304,P004,-3,2024-06-01,completed\n2006,305,P002,1,2024-06-01,shipped\n\"\"\"\n\nPRODUCTS_SOURCE = \"\"\"product_id,product_name,category,unit_price\nP001,Laptop Pro 15,Electronics,55000\nP002,Mechanical Keyboard,Peripherals,3200\nP003,USB-C Hub,Accessories,1200\nP004,4K Monitor,Electronics,18500\n\"\"\"\n\n# ── Step 1: EXTRACT ──────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef extract_orders():\n    \"\"\"Pull raw orders from source. In production: connect to a real DB or API.\"\"\"\n    print(\"  [EXTRACT] Pulling orders from source system...\")\n    df = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(ORDERS_SOURCE))\n    print(f\"            Got {len(df)} raw rows\")\n    return df\n\ndef extract_products():\n    \"\"\"Pull product reference data.\"\"\"\n    print(\"  [EXTRACT] Pulling product catalog...\")\n    df = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(PRODUCTS_SOURCE))\n    print(f\"            Got {len(df)} products\")\n    return df\n\n# ── Step 2: VALIDATE ─────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef validate(df):\n    \"\"\"\n    Run quality checks. Return (clean_df, quarantine_df).\n    We NEVER silently drop data — we quarantine it for review.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"  [VALIDATE] Running data quality checks...\")\n\n    bad_mask = (\n        df[\"order_id\"].isna() |\n        df[\"user_id\"].isna() |\n        df[\"quantity\"].isna() | (df[\"quantity\"] <= 0) |\n        df.duplicated(subset=[\"order_id\"], keep=\"first\")\n    )\n\n    clean = df[~bad_mask].copy()\n    quarantine = df[bad_mask].copy()\n\n    print(f\"            Passed: {len(clean)} rows\")\n    if len(quarantine) > 0:\n        print(f\"            Quarantined: {len(quarantine)} rows (see quarantine log)\")\n\n    return clean, quarantine\n\n# ── Step 3: TRANSFORM ────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef transform(orders_df, products_df):\n    \"\"\"\n    Clean, enrich, and model the data.\n    Output: one analytics-ready table.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"  [TRANSFORM] Enriching and modeling data...\")\n\n    # Parse dates\n    orders_df[\"order_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(orders_df[\"order_date\"])\n\n    # Join orders with product catalog (like a SQL JOIN)\n    df = orders_df.merge(products_df, on=\"product_id\", how=\"left\")\n\n    # Calculate derived fields\n    df[\"total_amount\"]    = df[\"quantity\"] * df[\"unit_price\"]\n    df[\"order_month\"]     = df[\"order_date\"].dt.to_period(\"M\").astype(str)\n    df[\"is_high_value\"]   = df[\"total_amount\"] >= 10000\n    df[\"pipeline_run_at\"] = datetime.now().strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\")\n\n    # Select final columns for the warehouse\n    final_cols = [\n        \"order_id\", \"user_id\", \"product_id\", \"product_name\", \"category\",\n        \"quantity\", \"unit_price\", \"total_amount\",\n        \"order_date\", \"order_month\", \"status\",\n        \"is_high_value\", \"pipeline_run_at\"\n    ]\n    df = df[final_cols]\n    print(f\"            Produced {len(df)} enriched rows\")\n    return df\n\n# ── Step 4: LOAD ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef load(df, destination=\"warehouse.orders_fact\"):\n    \"\"\"\n    Write to destination.\n    In production: df.to_sql(...) or BigQuery/Snowflake API.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(f\"  [LOAD] Writing {len(df)} rows to '{destination}'...\")\n    # Simulated write — in real life this hits a database\n    df.to_parquet(\"/tmp/warehouse_orders.parquet\", index=False)\n    print(f\"         Done!\")\n\n# ── Step 5: REPORT ───────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef report(df):\n    \"\"\"Print a summary of what was loaded.\"\"\"\n    print()\n    print(\"  [REPORT] Pipeline Summary\")\n    print(\"  \" + \"-\" * 45)\n    print(f\"  Orders processed:  {len(df)}\")\n    print(f\"  Total revenue:     ${df['total_amount'].sum():>12,.2f}\")\n    print(f\"  Avg order value:   ${df['total_amount'].mean():>12,.2f}\")\n    print(f\"  High-value orders: {df['is_high_value'].sum()}\")\n    print()\n    print(\"  Revenue by Category:\")\n    by_cat = df.groupby(\"category\")[\"total_amount\"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)\n    for cat, rev in by_cat.items():\n        print(f\"    {cat:<20} ${rev:>10,.2f}\")\n\n# ── ORCHESTRATOR: Run the full pipeline ──────────────────────\n\ndef run_pipeline():\n    start = datetime.now()\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n    print(f\"PIPELINE START: {start.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}\")\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n\n    # Extract\n    raw_orders   = extract_orders()\n    raw_products = extract_products()\n    print()\n\n    # Validate\n    clean_orders, quarantined = validate(raw_orders)\n    print()\n\n    # Transform\n    final_df = transform(clean_orders, raw_products)\n    print()\n\n    # Load\n    load(final_df)\n\n    # Report\n    report(final_df)\n\n    elapsed = (datetime.now() - start).total_seconds()\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n    print(f\"PIPELINE DONE in {elapsed:.2f}s\")\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n    return final_df\n\n# Run it!\nresult = run_pipeline()","metadata":{"executionCancelledAt":null,"executionTime":51,"lastExecutedAt":1773720945955,"lastExecutedByKernel":"c5df7cf6-b661-44e9-8e58-023bfb2fb3f3","lastScheduledRunId":null,"lastSuccessfullyExecutedCode":"# ============================================================\n# Full Production-Style ETL Pipeline\n# ============================================================\n\nimport pandas as pd\nimport io\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\n# ── Simulated source data ────────────────────────────────────\n\nORDERS_SOURCE = \"\"\"order_id,user_id,product_id,quantity,order_date,status\n2001,301,P001,1,2024-06-01,completed\n2002,302,P003,2,2024-06-01,completed\n2003,303,P002,1,2024-06-01,pending\n2004,301,P001,1,2024-06-01,completed\n2004,301,P001,1,2024-06-01,completed\n2005,304,P004,-3,2024-06-01,completed\n2006,305,P002,1,2024-06-01,shipped\n\"\"\"\n\nPRODUCTS_SOURCE = \"\"\"product_id,product_name,category,unit_price\nP001,Laptop Pro 15,Electronics,55000\nP002,Mechanical Keyboard,Peripherals,3200\nP003,USB-C Hub,Accessories,1200\nP004,4K Monitor,Electronics,18500\n\"\"\"\n\n# ── Step 1: EXTRACT ──────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef extract_orders():\n    \"\"\"Pull raw orders from source. In production: connect to a real DB or API.\"\"\"\n    print(\"  [EXTRACT] Pulling orders from source system...\")\n    df = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(ORDERS_SOURCE))\n    print(f\"            Got {len(df)} raw rows\")\n    return df\n\ndef extract_products():\n    \"\"\"Pull product reference data.\"\"\"\n    print(\"  [EXTRACT] Pulling product catalog...\")\n    df = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(PRODUCTS_SOURCE))\n    print(f\"            Got {len(df)} products\")\n    return df\n\n# ── Step 2: VALIDATE ─────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef validate(df):\n    \"\"\"\n    Run quality checks. Return (clean_df, quarantine_df).\n    We NEVER silently drop data — we quarantine it for review.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"  [VALIDATE] Running data quality checks...\")\n\n    bad_mask = (\n        df[\"order_id\"].isna() |\n        df[\"user_id\"].isna() |\n        df[\"quantity\"].isna() | (df[\"quantity\"] <= 0) |\n        df.duplicated(subset=[\"order_id\"], keep=\"first\")\n    )\n\n    clean = df[~bad_mask].copy()\n    quarantine = df[bad_mask].copy()\n\n    print(f\"            Passed: {len(clean)} rows\")\n    if len(quarantine) > 0:\n        print(f\"            Quarantined: {len(quarantine)} rows (see quarantine log)\")\n\n    return clean, quarantine\n\n# ── Step 3: TRANSFORM ────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef transform(orders_df, products_df):\n    \"\"\"\n    Clean, enrich, and model the data.\n    Output: one analytics-ready table.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"  [TRANSFORM] Enriching and modeling data...\")\n\n    # Parse dates\n    orders_df[\"order_date\"] = pd.to_datetime(orders_df[\"order_date\"])\n\n    # Join orders with product catalog (like a SQL JOIN)\n    df = orders_df.merge(products_df, on=\"product_id\", how=\"left\")\n\n    # Calculate derived fields\n    df[\"total_amount\"]    = df[\"quantity\"] * df[\"unit_price\"]\n    df[\"order_month\"]     = df[\"order_date\"].dt.to_period(\"M\").astype(str)\n    df[\"is_high_value\"]   = df[\"total_amount\"] >= 10000\n    df[\"pipeline_run_at\"] = datetime.now().strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\")\n\n    # Select final columns for the warehouse\n    final_cols = [\n        \"order_id\", \"user_id\", \"product_id\", \"product_name\", \"category\",\n        \"quantity\", \"unit_price\", \"total_amount\",\n        \"order_date\", \"order_month\", \"status\",\n        \"is_high_value\", \"pipeline_run_at\"\n    ]\n    df = df[final_cols]\n    print(f\"            Produced {len(df)} enriched rows\")\n    return df\n\n# ── Step 4: LOAD ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef load(df, destination=\"warehouse.orders_fact\"):\n    \"\"\"\n    Write to destination.\n    In production: df.to_sql(...) or BigQuery/Snowflake API.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(f\"  [LOAD] Writing {len(df)} rows to '{destination}'...\")\n    # Simulated write — in real life this hits a database\n    df.to_parquet(\"/tmp/warehouse_orders.parquet\", index=False)\n    print(f\"         Done!\")\n\n# ── Step 5: REPORT ───────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef report(df):\n    \"\"\"Print a summary of what was loaded.\"\"\"\n    print()\n    print(\"  [REPORT] Pipeline Summary\")\n    print(\"  \" + \"-\" * 45)\n    print(f\"  Orders processed:  {len(df)}\")\n    print(f\"  Total revenue:     ${df['total_amount'].sum():>12,.2f}\")\n    print(f\"  Avg order value:   ${df['total_amount'].mean():>12,.2f}\")\n    print(f\"  High-value orders: {df['is_high_value'].sum()}\")\n    print()\n    print(\"  Revenue by Category:\")\n    by_cat = df.groupby(\"category\")[\"total_amount\"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)\n    for cat, rev in by_cat.items():\n        print(f\"    {cat:<20} ${rev:>10,.2f}\")\n\n# ── ORCHESTRATOR: Run the full pipeline ──────────────────────\n\ndef run_pipeline():\n    start = datetime.now()\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n    print(f\"PIPELINE START: {start.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}\")\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n\n    # Extract\n    raw_orders   = extract_orders()\n    raw_products = extract_products()\n    print()\n\n    # Validate\n    clean_orders, quarantined = validate(raw_orders)\n    print()\n\n    # Transform\n    final_df = transform(clean_orders, raw_products)\n    print()\n\n    # Load\n    load(final_df)\n\n    # Report\n    report(final_df)\n\n    elapsed = (datetime.now() - start).total_seconds()\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n    print(f\"PIPELINE DONE in {elapsed:.2f}s\")\n    print(\"=\" * 50)\n    return final_df\n\n# Run it!\nresult = run_pipeline()"},"cell_type":"code","id":"6056a367-a585-427d-80ad-3ca8181ecfa3","outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":"==================================================\nPIPELINE START: 2026-03-17 04:15:45\n==================================================\n  [EXTRACT] Pulling orders from source system...\n            Got 7 raw rows\n  [EXTRACT] Pulling product catalog...\n            Got 4 products\n\n  [VALIDATE] Running data quality checks...\n            Passed: 5 rows\n            Quarantined: 2 rows (see quarantine log)\n\n  [TRANSFORM] Enriching and modeling data...\n            Produced 5 enriched rows\n\n  [LOAD] Writing 5 rows to 'warehouse.orders_fact'...\n         Done!\n\n  [REPORT] Pipeline Summary\n  ---------------------------------------------\n  Orders processed:  5\n  Total revenue:     $  118,800.00\n  Avg order value:   $   23,760.00\n  High-value orders: 2\n\n  Revenue by Category:\n    Electronics          $110,000.00\n    Peripherals          $  6,400.00\n    Accessories          $  2,400.00\n==================================================\nPIPELINE DONE in 0.01s\n==================================================\n"}],"execution